In the context of a Stored Value facility, a Payment Service Provider has the obligation to safeguard funds equivalent to the Stored Value issued by:

(a) maintaining a separate account or segregated funds to hold the equivalent value of the Stored Value issued to Payment Service Users ( aligning with the Rule requiring safeguarding of Money held or controlled on behalf of a Payment Service User);

(b) ensuring that such funds are identifiable and accounted for separately from the Payment Service Provider's own funds (consistent with the requirement for a Captive Insurer to maintain adequate accounting and other records to identify contracts and assets, liabilities, revenues, and expenses attributable to the Long-Term Insurance Fund);

(c) implementing robust controls and systems to prevent Financial Crime, such as money laundering, transaction fraud, or theft of digitally stored CDD documentation, associated with the Stored Value facility (in line with the requirement for a Relevant Person's AML/TFS policies, procedures, systems, and controls to ensure compliance with Federal AML Legislation and detect suspicious Persons and Transactions);

(d) having an operational risk assessment system in place to monitor and control the operational risk profile of the Stored Value facility (integrating it into the risk management processes, similar to the requirement for a Recognised Clearing House);

(e) maintaining an audit trail of Transactions related to the Stored Value facility (consistent with the requirement for a Relevant Person to provide an appropriate audit trail of a Transaction); and

(f) ensuring compliance with all other obligations in the Rules, including proportionality considerations for capital requirements and sustainability practices (aligning with COBS Rule 22.10 and the Spot Commodities Framework).

By fulfilling these obligations, a Payment Service Provider can ensure the safeguarding of funds equivalent to the Stored Value issued, thereby protecting the interests of Payment Service Users and maintaining the integrity of the Stored Value facility.

